---
import BlogPost from '../../../../layouts/BlogPost.astro';
import { BLOG_POSTS } from '../../../../data/blog';

const meta = BLOG_POSTS.find((p) => p.slug === '1099-only-mortgage-contractors')!;

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'How does a 1099 Only mortgage differ from a Bank Statement loan?',
    answer:
      'A 1099 Only mortgage qualifies on gross 1099 income reported by clients — typically one or two years of 1099 forms — with a fixed expense-factor haircut. A Bank Statement loan qualifies on bank deposits over 12 or 24 months with a variable expense factor. 1099 Only is usually simpler and faster to document; Bank Statement can produce a higher qualifying number for borrowers with deposits significantly above their 1099 totals.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Can I qualify on one year of 1099s?',
    answer:
      'Some lenders, Clout included, allow one-year 1099 qualification when the borrower has a documented 2+ year history in the same line of work. The lender will look at the prior year\'s Schedule C or 1040 to confirm consistency. Two years of 1099s is the standard and produces the best pricing.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Do I have to be paid by a single 1099 client?',
    answer:
      'No. Multiple 1099 clients are fully eligible — common for consultants, freelancers, and gig workers. The lender will sum the 1099s across clients and treat the total as the gross qualifying income. Source documentation (the 1099s themselves, signed and matching the tax return totals) is required.',
  },
];
---

<BlogPost
  slug={meta.slug}
  title={meta.title}
  description={meta.description}
  category={meta.category}
  datePublished={meta.datePublished}
  dateModified={meta.dateModified}
  lead="A 1099 Only mortgage qualifies independent contractors and gig workers using gross 1099 income — not net Schedule C after deductions. For high-earning contractors who legally write off heavily, the qualifying income on a 1099 Only file is often 2 to 3 times what a conventional lender would calculate."
  faqs={faqs}
>
  <h2>Why Schedule C kills conventional qualification</h2>
  <p>
    The independent contractor problem: a freelancer earns $180K of gross 1099 income, then
    legally deducts $90K of business expenses on Schedule C (home office, equipment, mileage,
    health insurance, retirement contributions, professional development). The Schedule C
    net comes in at $90K. A conventional mortgage underwriter uses that lower number for DTI.
    The qualifying income is half of what the borrower actually earned. A 1099 Only mortgage
    skips Schedule C entirely — the underwriter reads the 1099s directly.
  </p>

  <h2>How Clout calculates 1099 Only income</h2>
  <p>
    The math is straightforward:
  </p>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Sum gross 1099 totals</strong> across all client 1099s for the qualifying year (or two-year average if available).</li>
    <li><strong>Apply a fixed expense factor</strong> — typically 10–15% on most 1099 programs. The expense factor is meant to roughly approximate non-discretionary business costs without requiring a Schedule C analysis.</li>
    <li><strong>Divide by 12</strong> to get monthly qualifying income for DTI.</li>
  </ol>
  <p>
    Worked example: a software consultant with $180K of gross 1099 income at a 10% expense
    factor produces $162K qualifying ($13,500/month). A Schedule C-based conventional file
    might calculate the same borrower at $7,500/month. Same person, same year, 80% larger
    qualifying number.
  </p>

  <div class="key-stats">
    <div><span class="k">Min FICO</span><span class="v">620</span></div>
    <div><span class="k">Qualifying period</span><span class="v">1 or 2 years of 1099s</span></div>
    <div><span class="k">Typical expense factor</span><span class="v">10–15%</span></div>
  </div>

  <h2>What the file needs to include</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>The 1099s themselves (1099-NEC most commonly; 1099-MISC and 1099-K also accepted).</li>
    <li>Signed federal tax return for the qualifying year(s) showing 1099 totals.</li>
    <li>YTD income verification — a current-year bank statement showing deposits consistent with the 1099 pace, or a YTD client letter on letterhead.</li>
    <li>Business license, DBA filing, or W-9 confirming 2+ years self-employment history.</li>
    <li>CPA letter is helpful but not always required.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>When 1099 Only is not the right fit</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>W-2 income is the dominant earning stream — conventional usually qualifies cleanly.</li>
    <li>1099 income is small or inconsistent — a Bank Statement loan may produce a higher number.</li>
    <li>The borrower has both 1099 and W-2 income in roughly equal measure — a hybrid program or full doc with carve-outs may price better.</li>
    <li>The borrower has heavy Schedule C profit (low deductions) — conventional pricing usually beats Non-QM.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Common files that close on 1099 Only</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Software engineers and product designers on long-term contracts.</li>
    <li>Realtors paid via 1099 commissions.</li>
    <li>Sales reps on draw-plus-commission 1099 structures.</li>
    <li>Healthcare workers — locum tenens physicians, traveling nurses on agency 1099s.</li>
    <li>Creative professionals — videographers, photographers, consultants billing multiple clients.</li>
    <li>Trades — independent contractors not formally incorporated as LLCs.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Frequently asked</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    {faqs.map((f) => (
      <details>
        <summary>{f.question}</summary>
        <div><p>{f.answer}</p></div>
      </details>
    ))}
  </div>

  <h2>Next steps</h2>
  <p>
    Brokers placing 1099 Only files: confirm the expense factor and qualifying-year rules for
    the specific program in <a href="/tpo-connect/">TPO Connect</a>. Borrowers: <a href="/contact/">contact
    Clout</a> for a same-day eligibility read. Related: <a href="/resources/blog/bank-statement-loans-self-employed/">Bank Statement Loans</a> ·
    <a href="/loan-options/1099-only/">1099 Only program page</a> ·
    <a href="/resources/glossary/#1099-only-mortgage">1099 Only</a> in the glossary.
  </p>
</BlogPost>
